{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0148rN4ycmpCbNM5HhwAtP8b","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This involves the AI vision model classifying the image AND the system's decision to hold vs publish. The failure could be: (a) the AI model doesn't flag it, or (b) even if flagged, the routing logic sends it to publish anyway. \n- REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network/subprocess needed for the routing logic part. But the classification requires a real AI vision model.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - correctness depends on what the real AI vision model produces. \n\nThe core question is whether the model actually detects explicit content accurately, since a stub would always pass. This is fundamentally about the real vision model's capability, making it an agentic-level test.\n\n**Behavior 2: A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: The behavior specifically asks about obfuscation resistance - this is about the AI text model's robustness to obfuscation.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - whether the model handles obfuscation is fundamentally a question of AI model quality/capability. A stub can't test this.\n- MULTI-STEP: Single step.\n\nMinimum level: **Agentic** - robustness to obfuscation is a model quality question that only a real AI model can answer.\n\n**Behavior 3: A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.**\n\nFor this one, I'm looking at the routing and decision logic after both checks pass. The question is whether the system correctly publishes when both models return \"safe\" - and since the routing logic is deterministic, I can stub both AI responses and test just the logic path.\n\nMinimum level: **Integration** - I'd test the pipeline with stubbed AI responses returning \"safe\" to verify the system publishes correctly. The failure mode would be a bug in the publish logic itself, not the AI classification.\n\nBut I need to think through whether testing \"passes both checks\" actually requires real AI models to classify correctly, or if it's just about the routing logic given that both checks return pass. The behavior statement focuses on what happens when both pass, so the key is whether the system publishes - that's a logic test, not an AI quality test.\n\nFor the latency behavior, this is trickier - the 5-second SLA depends heavily on real AI model response times, so stubbed models would only measure pipeline overhead, not actual performance under load.\n\nThe behavior chains multiple AI calls in sequence (image check → text check → publish), which makes this a workflow test rather than a simple unit test.\n\nFor the error handling when the AI vision model is unavailable, I can stub the model to throw a service unavailable error and verify the system queues for retry instead of auto-approving. The failure mode lives in the routing logic, not in AI quality, so I don't need the real model to be down—just a mock that simulates the failure. This is an integration-level test since I'm verifying the error handling path through the pipeline with a stubbed dependency.\n\nFor consistency of moderation decisions on borderline images, this is fundamentally about whether the real AI model produces consistent results across multiple submissions. A stub would always return the same thing by definition, which would hide any actual inconsistency in the model's output. This needs to run at the agentic level to test real model behavior.\n\nLooking at my classification now: behaviors 1, 2, and 6 require the real AI models since they're testing the actual classification quality and consistency. Behavior 3 is integration-level since it's just testing routing logic with stubbed responses. Behavior 5 is also integration-level for error handling. But behavior 4 is trickier—the 5-second SLA involves real timing, and if I stub the AI calls at integration level, I'd only measure pipeline overhead, not the actual latency from the AI models themselves. The real failure scenario is when the AI takes too long, so I need the real models running to properly test this constraint.\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence scores for each behavior across the test levels, making sure they sum to 1.0 for each one.\n\nFor the \"safe post published\" behavior, I need to reconsider—it's really about the integration between the content checks and the publishing system, so Integration should carry the highest weight, with Unit tests catching some edge cases and the other levels having minimal probability.\n\nFor the 5-second SLA, Workflow is most likely since it involves orchestrating multiple AI steps with real latency, though Agentic could also apply if the agent itself is managing the timing.\n\nThe \"unavailable model → queue\" behavior points to Integration since it's about how the system handles external service failures, with System-level concerns about resilience also playing a role.\n\nFor consistency on borderline cases, Agentic is strongest because the AI model's behavior is what determines consistency, though Workflow could matter if orchestration affects the outcome.\n\nLet me refine these probabilities to be more precise about what each behavior is really testing. word \"silently dropped\" is interesting - this could be a bug in the routing/decision logic. With stubbed AI responses returning \"safe\", this is testing Integration (module wiring). Unit could work for just the decision logic function. But since the behavior involves the pipeline routing, I'll go with Integration.\n\nFor behavior 5, when the AI vision model is unavailable and image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved, I can simulate that failure mode with a stub that throws a connection error to test the routing logic's response. That's clearly Integration.\n\nReconsidering behavior 4 though - it explicitly mentions the full pipeline with image check, text check, and publish decision sequencing together. That's multiple AI model calls in sequence, which points to Workflow level rather than Agentic, since the latency depends on the non-deterministic AI response times across the entire run.\n\nSo my final assessment is behavior 4 is Workflow minimum, while behaviors 1, 2, and 6 are Agentic minimum, and behaviors 3 and 5 are Integration minimum.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10028,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10028},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e64afa9d-8df4-4e1a-8869-35bd2b809bd2","uuid":"e959cd94-cc72-41b5-a598-84fe594fb462"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0148rN4ycmpCbNM5HhwAtP8b","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Q6rZiUh2ZCnyiWS2CE8JUb","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is whether the real AI vision model correctly classifies explicit content — not just whether the routing logic routes a flagged result to review. MOCK-HIDE: A stub that always returns 'flagged' trivially passes; a stub that returns 'safe' trivially fails. Neither reveals whether the real model detects explicit content. LLM-DEP: Classification quality is the core question here — does the model reliably flag explicit images? That is non-deterministic and AI-quality-dependent, requiring the real vision model. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was rejected because the routing logic (flagged → hold) is only half the behavior; the other half is whether the model actually flags the image. The behavior text says 'an image containing explicit content is flagged' — the flagging itself depends on real model output.","test_description":"Submit a set of images with known-explicit content to the real AI vision model through the moderation pipeline and assert each is held for human review rather than published. Use a real (or real-equivalent staging) vision model endpoint to verify the model's classification is correct, not just that routing logic handles a pre-classified result.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.12}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Robustness to obfuscation is a property of the AI text model's generalization ability, not of any routing or parsing logic. The failure lives entirely inside the model. LLM-DEP: Whether the model sees through letter substitutions and unicode lookalikes is an AI quality/capability question. A stub that returns 'flagged' for any input trivially passes; the real failure — model missing obfuscated hate speech — only surfaces with the real model. MOCK-HIDE: Any deterministic stub hides this failure completely. REJECTION-GATE: Integration rejected because no amount of module wiring tests whether the model handles obfuscation; Unit rejected because there is no local parsing/algorithm to unit-test here — the behavior is entirely about model robustness.","test_description":"Submit text posts containing hate speech in multiple obfuscated forms (letter substitution, unicode homoglyphs, l33tspeak variants) to the real AI text classifier and assert each is flagged. The test must run against the real model to expose any obfuscation blind spots.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.83,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode here is in the routing/decision logic: given that both the image check module and the text check module return 'safe', does the pipeline correctly publish rather than silently drop or incorrectly hold? This is a module-boundary failure, not a model-quality failure. LLM-DEP: The behavior presupposes the post passed both checks — 'passes both content checks' — so the AI model output is an input assumption, not the variable under test. Stubs returning 'safe' faithfully represent this. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking does NOT hide the failure; the failure is in the downstream decision logic. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network/subprocess needed. (b) Correctness does not depend on real AI output — we assume safe classifications as inputs. (c) No chained agentic steps. Integration is appropriate.","test_description":"Wire the image-check module, text-check module, and publish-decision module together with stubbed AI clients that return 'safe' classifications. Submit a benign post and assert it reaches the published state with no errors, no hold queue entry, and no silent drop (e.g., verify a publish event or published record exists).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full moderation pipeline — image check, text check, publish decision — completes within 5 seconds of submission.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"REAL-INFRA: Latency under real load depends on real AI model response times, not pipeline overhead alone. A stub with instant returns measures nothing meaningful about the 5-second SLA. LLM-DEP: Real AI model calls have non-deterministic, variable latency. Stubs always pass this test trivially. MULTI-STEP: The behavior explicitly describes a sequence of two AI model calls (image check → text check) plus a publish decision — multiple agentic steps chained end-to-end. This satisfies MULTI-STEP → Workflow. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic (single model step) was rejected because the behavior explicitly names a two-step AI pipeline: 'image check, text check, publish decision'; these are sequential agentic operations, not a single call. System was rejected because the bottleneck is AI model latency, not OS/subprocess behavior.","test_description":"Submit a post through the complete moderation pipeline using real AI model endpoints (image classifier and text classifier) and measure wall-clock time from submission to publish/hold decision. Assert the full round-trip completes within 5 seconds. Run across a sample of posts to account for model latency variance. Test under realistic concurrency to surface queuing delays.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.26,"Workflow":0.55}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in the error-handling routing logic: when the vision model client returns an error (connection refused, timeout, 503), does the pipeline route the post to a retry queue or incorrectly auto-approve it? This is a module-boundary failure between the vision model client and the decision/queue module. LLM-DEP: This is error handling, not AI classification quality. The 'unavailability' can be faithfully simulated by a stub that raises a connection error — no real AI model needed to catch the routing bug. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking does NOT hide the failure; the failure is in what happens after the client raises, not in what the model returns. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) Real network unavailability is not needed — an in-process stub raising an exception reproduces the exact failure mode. (b) No AI output quality dependency. (c) No chained agentic steps. Integration holds.","test_description":"Wire the vision model client (stubbed to raise a ServiceUnavailableError), the image moderation handler, and the retry queue together. Submit an image post and assert: (1) no publish record is created, (2) a retry queue entry is created for the post, and (3) the post is not marked as auto-approved. Also verify a legitimate unavailability error is not silently swallowed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The moderation decision for a borderline image is consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Consistency of output on borderline cases is a property of the real AI model's behavior, not of any routing or caching logic. The failure — model flip-flopping on the same borderline image — only surfaces with the real model. LLM-DEP: This is explicitly about non-determinism in AI model output. A stub always returns the same result (perfectly consistent by construction), completely hiding any real inconsistency. MOCK-HIDE: Any deterministic stub makes this test trivially pass. REJECTION-GATE: Integration rejected because no amount of in-process module wiring reveals whether the real model is consistent; the failure is inside the model itself. Workflow rejected because this is a single-step classification call repeated, not a multi-step agentic pipeline.","test_description":"Submit the same borderline image (pre-selected as a known near-threshold case) to the real AI vision model N times in quick succession (e.g., 10 submissions within a 30-second window) and assert the moderation decision (hold vs. publish) is identical across all N submissions. Fail if any submission yields a different outcome, flagging real model inconsistency.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.1}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10028,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10028},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e64afa9d-8df4-4e1a-8869-35bd2b809bd2","uuid":"6883713c-92b2-4cdd-864e-6c87e752ce98"}
